
1. What a callback function is
A callback function is simply:

A function passed into another function as an argument, to be executed later.

Simple Example:
function processUserInput(callback) {
  console.log("Processing...");
  callback();
}

function sayHi() {
  console.log("Hi!");
}

processUserInput(sayHi);

👉 Here, sayHi is the callback function.


2. Why callbacks are used in asynchronous programming
JavaScript is non-blocking, meaning it doesn’t wait for tasks like:

API calls
File reading
Timers

Callbacks let us run code after a task finishes.
Example with setTimeout:
console.log("Start");

setTimeout(function() {
  console.log("Executed after 2 seconds");
}, 2000);

console.log("End");
Output:
Start
End
Executed after 2 seconds

👉 The callback runs after the delay, without blocking execution

3. Passing functions as arguments
function calculate(a, b, operation) {
  return operation(a, b);
}

function add(x, y) {
  return x + y;
}

console.log(calculate(2, 3, add)); // 5





Callback usage in common scenarios
1. Timers
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Done!");
}, 1000);
2. Event Handling
button.addEventListener("click", function() {
  console.log("Button clicked!");
});
3. API Calls (Simplified)
fetch("https://api.example.com/data")
  .then(function(response) {
    return response.json();
  })
  .then(function(data) {
    console.log(data);
  });

Main Function
     |
     ↓
Calls Another Function
     |
     ↓
Passes Callback
     |
     ↓
Callback Executes Later

Basic problem of callback nesting

hen callbacks are inside callbacks, code becomes hard to read.

Example:
setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("Step 1");

  setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Step 2");

    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log("Step 3");
    }, 1000);

  }, 1000);

}, 1000);
8. Nested Callback Flow Diagram
Step 1
  ↓
Step 2
  ↓
Step 3

But in code:

Callback
 └── Callback
      └── Callback
9. Problems with Callback Nesting
❌ Hard to read (pyramid shape)
❌ Difficult to debug
❌ Error handling becomes messy
❌ Not scalable

This is often called:

"Callback Hell" or "Pyramid of Doom"

To solve callback problems, JavaScript introduced:

Promises
Async/Await
